value.value: The assembly and secretion of an extracellular exosome, a membrane-bounded vesicle that is released into the extracellular region by fusion of the limiting endosomal membrane of a multivesicular body with the plasma membrane.

The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a post-synaptic potential responsible for muscle contraction.

label.value: neuromuscular junction of skeletal muscle fiber

value.value: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a skeletal muscle fiber.

definition.value: In vertebrates, the term 'neuromuscular junction' is limited to synapses targeting skeletal muscle fibers - all of which are cholinergic and excitatory. Both inhibitory and excitatory neuromuscular junctions exist in invertebrates, utilizing a range of neurotransmitters including glutamate, GABA and 5-HT.

value.value: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a myotube.

definition.value: In vertebrates, the term 'neuromuscular junction' is limited to synapses targeting the myotubes of skeletal muscle (AKA skeletal muscle fibers). Neuromuscular junctions targeting other muscle cell types exist in invertebrates such as the mononucleate somatic muscles of nematodes.

label.value: neuromuscular junction of somatic muscle myotube

value.value: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a somatic muscle myotube, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cell.

label.value: excitatory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube

value.value: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the excitation of somatic muscle myotubes, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cells.
A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a somatic muscle cell, such as those found in nematodes and arthropods.

The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a skeletal muscle fiber cell. Skeletal muscle fiber differentiation starts with myoblast fusion and the appearance of specific cell markers (this is the cell development step). Then individual skeletal muscle fibers fuse to form bigger myotubes and start to contract.

label.value: neuromuscular junction development, skeletal muscle fiber

value.value: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a neuromuscular junction that targets a skeletal muscle fiber.

A DNA-binding transcription factor activity regulated by binding to a ligand and that modulates the transcription of specific genes and gene sets. Examples include the lac and trp repressors in E.coli and steroid hormone receptors.

definition.value: For usage guidance, see comment in GO:0003700 ; DNA-binding transcription factor activity.

value.value: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of another organism that act to protect the cell or organism from damage caused by that organism.

Any process in which a protein complex is maintained in a location and prevented from moving elsewhere. These include sequestration, stabilization to prevent transport elsewhere and the active retrieval of protein complexes that move away.

label.value: maintenance of protein complex location in cytoplasm

value.value: Any process in which a protein complex is maintained in a specific location within the cytoplasm and is prevented from moving elsewhere.
A vocalization behavior that is the result of learning.

definition.value: Examples include human speech and learned bird song.

value.value: The lipid bilayer that forms the outer-most layer of an organelle.

definition.value: Examples include the outer membranes of double membrane bound organelles such as mitochondria as well as the bounding membranes of single-membrane bound organelles such as lysosomes.

value.value: A membrane that is a (regional) part of the plasma membrane.

definition.value: Note that this term should not be used for direct manual annotation as it should always be possible to choose a more specific subclass.

value.value: A secretory granule that contains mucin.

label.value: learned vocalization behavior or vocal learning

value.value: Vocalisation behavior that is the result of learning, or the process by which new vocalizations are learned.

definition.value: This grouping term is necessary because, in the absence of conditional mutations, it is not possible to use phenotypic evidence to distinguish an effect on vocal learning from an effect on learned vocalisation behavior.

value.value: The attachment of one cell to another cell via adhesion molecules.

The binding by a cell-adhesion protein on a cell surface to an adhesion molecule on another cell surface or an external substrate, to mediate adhesion of the cell to the external substrate or to another cell.
The binding by a cell-adhesion protein on the cell surface to an extracellular matrix component, to mediate adhesion of the cell to another cell.
Binding to a collagen fibril.

label.value: protein complex involved in cell-cell adhesion

value.value: Any protein complex that is capable of carrying out some part of the process of cell-cell adhesion.

label.value: protein complex involved in cell adhesion

value.value: Any protein complex that is capable of carrying out some part of the process of cell adhesion to the cell matrix or to another cell.

label.value: cadherin binding involved in cell-cell adhesion

value.value: Any cadherin binding that occurs as part of the process of cell-cell adhesion.
A collagen trimer that forms networks.
A supramolecular assembly of fibrillar collagen complexes in the form of a long fiber (fibril) with transverse striations (bands).
A complex of collagen trimers such as a fibril or collagen network.
A supramolecular complex that consists of collagen triple helices associated to form a network.
Any collagen timer that is part of a basement membrane.
The process in which a monoatomic cation is transported across a membrane. Monatomic cations (also called simple cations) are positively charged ions consisting of exactly one atom.
The directed movement of some substance from outside of a cell into a cell. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

label.value: inorganic anion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of inorganic anions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: inorganic cation import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of inorganic cations from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The process in which an inorganic ion is transported across a membrane.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: The process in which an inorganic anion is transported across a membrane.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

value.value: A process in which an inorganic cation is transported from one side of a membrane to the other by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

definition.value: Note that this term is not intended for use in annotating lateral movement within membranes.

label.value: G protein-coupled serotonin receptor signaling pathway

value.value: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G protein-coupled serotonin receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.
A protein complex that is capable of G protein-coupled serotonin receptor activity.
A synapse that uses dopamine as a neurotransmitter.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the synaptic vesicle cycle.
The directed movement of adenine from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: calcium ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of calcium ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of a carbohydrate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of glucose from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: iron ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of iron ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of L-glutamate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: sodium ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of sodium ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
Division of a stem cell during which it retains its identity and buds off a daughter cell with a new identity.
A myofibril of a skeletal muscle fiber.
